Amanita phalloides is a highly toxic mushroom species that belongs to the Amanita genus.
It has a conical or bell-shaped cap that ranges in color from light green to yellowish-brown.
The mushroom's stem is white and has a prominent bulb at the base, covered by a thin white veil.
The gills underneath the cap are white and crowded together, turning yellowish-green as the mushroom matures.
The cap's surface is smooth and can be slightly shiny, with a distinctive white margin around the cap's edge.
Amanita phalloides grows in woodlands and can be found in Europe, Asia, and North America.
Unfortunately, the mushroom's highly toxic and deadly in nature, making it important to avoid it if seen in the wild.
